1. Requiremment Clarification

    i. Functional Requirement

        -> Traffic Distribution: Distribute incoming requests across multiple backend servers using configurable algorithms.
        -> Health Checking: Continuously monitor backend servers and automatically remove unhealthy ones from the pool.
        -> Session Persistence: Support sticky sessions to route requests from the same client to the same server.
        -> SSL Termination: Handle SSL/TLS encryption and decryption to offload work from backend servers.
        -> Layer 4 and Layer 7 Support: Support both transport-level (TCP/UDP) and application-level (HTTP/HTTPS) load balancing.


    ii. Non-Functional Requirements

        -> High Availability: The load balancer must be highly available (99.99% uptime) with no single point of failure.
        -> Low Latency: Should add minimal latency to requests (< 1ms overhead).
        -> High Throughput: Handle up to 1 million requests per second at peak.
        -> Scalability: Should scale horizontally to handle increasing traffic.
        -> Fault Tolerance: Continue operating even when individual components fail.


2. Metrices

    i. Traffic Estimates

        Peak Traffic: 1M request per second
        Average Traffic: 300K request per second
        Concurrent Connections: 500k

    ii. Bandwidth Estimates

        Average request size:  ~2 KB (HTTP headers + small payload)
        Average response size: ~10 KB (typical API response)

        Ingress bandwidth = 1M RPS × 2 KB = 2 GB/s
        Egress bandwidth  = 1M RPS × 10 KB = 10 GB/s
        Total bandwidth   = 12 GB/s = ~96 Gbps

    iii. Health Check Overhead

        With 1,000 backend servers and checks every 5 seconds:

            Health check traffic = 1,000 servers / 5 seconds = 200 checks/second

    iv. Memory Requirements

        Each active connection needs state tracking in memory:

            Source IP + port	            6 bytes
            Destination IP + port	        6 bytes
            Connection state	            4 bytes
            Timestamps	                    16 bytes
            Protocol-specific data	        ~200 bytes
            Buffer space	                ~250 bytes
            Total per connection	        ~500 bytes

        For 500,000 concurrent connections:

        Connection state memory = 500,000 × 500 bytes = 250 MB

    v. Key Insights

        i. Network bandwidth is the primary constraint. At 12 GB/s, we need high-speed networking and likely multiple load balancer nodes.
        ii. Memory is not a concern. Connection tracking is cheap. Even 10x our estimate would only be 2.5 GB.
        iii. Health checks are lightweight. 200 checks per second is nothing compared to 1M requests per second.
        iv. Horizontal scaling is necessary. A single machine cannot handle 100 Gbps of traffic. We need to design for multiple load balancer nodes from the start.



3. Core APIs

    A load balancer has two distinct interfaces. 
        
        i. The data plane handles actual traffic (this is where millions of requests flow through), and 
        ii. the control plane handles configuration and management (registering backends, changing algorithms, viewing health status).

    The data plane is implicit since it just forwards network traffic. The control plane needs explicit APIs for operators to manage the system.


    i. Register Backend Server

        Url: POST /backends

        Payload: {
                    "address": "10.0.1.15",
                    "port": 8080,
                    "weight": 2,
                    "health_check_path": "/healthz"
                }


        Response: {
                "backend_id": "backend-a1b2c3",
                "status": "unknown", //(healthy, unhealthy can come later)
                "message": "Backend registered. Health check pending."
            }

        
    ii. Remove Backend Servers

        Url: DELETE /backends/{backend_id}

        Response {
                "message": "Backend removed successfully",
                "backend_id": "backend-a1b2c3",
                "drained_connections": 42
            }

        The drained_connections field tells you how many connections were in progress when the backend was removed.


    iii. Get Backend Health Status

        Url: GET /backends/{backend_id}/health

        Response: {
                "backend_id": "backend-a1b2c3",
                "status": "healthy",
                "last_check": "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z",
                "response_time_ms": 12,
                "active_connections": 847,
                "total_requests": 1250000,
                "failed_requests": 23
            }

        
    iv. Configure Load Balancing Algorithm

        Url: PUT /config/algorithm

        Payload: {
                "algorithm": "least_connections",
                "sticky_sessions": true,
                "sticky_ttl_seconds": 1800
            }

        
        algorithm -> One of: round_robin, weighted_round_robin, least_connections, ip_hash, random
        sticky_sessions -> Enable session persistence (default: false)
        sticky_ttl_seconds -> How long sticky sessions last (default: 3600)

    
        Response: {
                "message": "Configuration updated",
                "algorithm": "least_connections",
                "sticky_sessions": true
            }



4. Database Schema

    BackendServer

        backend_id       String (PK)	Unique identifier (e.g., "backend-a1b2c3")
        address	         String	        IP address or hostname
        port	         Integer	    Port the server listens on
        weight	         Integer	    Weight for weighted algorithms (default: 1)
        max_connections	 Integer	    Maximum concurrent connections (0 = unlimited)
        enabled	         Boolean	    Administrative toggle to disable without removing
        created_at	     Timestamp	    When this backend was registered
        updated_at       Timestamp	    Last configuration change


    Session Store Schema (Redis)

        Key:   sticky:{client_identifier}
        Value: backend-a1b2c3
        TTL:   1800 seconds (30 minutes, configurable)


        When a request arrives:

            Look up sticky:{client_identifier} in Redis
            If found and the backend is healthy, route to that backend
            If not found (or backend is unhealthy), apply normal algorithm and store the mapping


5. HLD

    Our load balancer needs to do three fundamental things:

        1. Distribute Traffic: Accept incoming requests and forward them to healthy backend servers.
        2. Monitor Health: Continuously check backends and route around failures.
        3. Stay Available: The load balancer itself cannot be a single point of failure.


        1. Distribute Traffic: Accept incoming requests and forward them to healthy backend servers.

            Components:

                i. Client

                ii. Frontend Listeners: This is the entry point for all client traffic

                iii. Routing Engine: This is the brain of the load balancer. Given a connection, the routing engine decides which backend server should handle it.


        2. Monitor Health: Continuously check backends and route around failures.

            The health checker is responsible for:

                i. Sending periodic probes to each backend (typically every 5-10 seconds)
                ii. Tracking the history of successes and failures
                iii. Deciding when a backend should be marked unhealthy (usually after 2-3 consecutive failures)
                iv. Deciding when an unhealthy backend can be marked healthy again (after 2-3 consecutive successes)
                v. Notifying the routing engine whenever a backend's status changes

            Components:

                i. Health Checker: Checks health in loop (Backend1, Backend2, ...)

                ii. Reouting Engine: same above one


            FLow:

                i. Continuous monitoring: The health checker sends probes to each backend every 5 seconds. Backends 1 and 3 respond with 200 OK. Backend 2 does not respond within the timeout.
                ii. Failure tracking: One failed check is not enough to mark a backend unhealthy (it could be a network blip). After 3 consecutive failures, Backend 2 is marked unhealthy.
                iii. Status update: The health checker notifies the routing engine that Backend 2 is now unhealthy.
                iv. Traffic rerouting: The routing engine immediately stops sending new traffic to Backend 2. Only Backends 1 and 3 receive requests.
                v. Recovery: If Backend 2 starts responding again, it needs to pass several consecutive health checks before being marked healthy and returned to the pool. This prevents flapping (rapidly switching between healthy and unhealthy).


        3. Stay Available: The load balancer itself cannot be a single point of failure.

            Run multiple load balancer instances to avoid Single Point of failure

            Problem with this

                i. How do clients know which instance to connect to?
                ii. What happens when one instance fails?
                iii. How do we handle state (like sticky sessions) across multiple instances?


            Pattern 1: Active-Passive (Failover): one load balancer handles all traffic while a backup waits idle, ready to take over if the primary fails.

            Pattern 2: Active-Active: In this pattern, multiple load balancer nodes handle traffic simultaneously. If one fails, the others continue without interruption.

                Traffic is distributed across multiple load balancer nodes using one of several methods:

                    DNS round-robin: DNS returns multiple IP addresses, and clients pick one. Not ideal since DNS caching can cause uneven distribution and slow failover.




6. Design Deep Dive (LLD)

    i. Load Balancing Algorithms

        Algorithm	       Complexity	    Statefulness	Adaptiveness	Best For

        Round Robin	        Very simple	    Stateless	       None	        Homogeneous backends, uniform requests
        Weighted            Round Robin	    Simple Stateless   None	        Known capacity differences
        Least Connections   Moderate	    Per-node state	   High	        Variable request processing times
        Weighted Least Conn	Moderate	    Per-node state	   High	        Production with mixed servers
        IP Hash	            Simple	        Stateless	       None	        Basic session persistence
        Consistent Hash	    Complex	        Stateless	       None	        Dynamic scaling, caching



    ii. Layer 4 vs Layer 7 Load Balancing

        Layer 4: A Layer 4 load balancer operates at the transport layer. It sees TCP/UDP packets but does not understand what is inside them. It makes routing decisions based only on:

            i. Source and destination IP addresses
            ii. Source and destination ports
            iii. Protocol (TCP or UDP)

            What L4 can do:
                -> Route based on port (send traffic on port 80 to web servers, port 3306 to database servers)
                -> Session persistence based on client IP
                -> Health checks (TCP connection success/failure)


        Layer 7: A Layer 7 load balancer operates at the application layer. It understands HTTP (and sometimes other protocols) and can make intelligent routing decisions based on request content.

            -> Route based on URL path (/api goes to API servers, /static goes to CDN)
            -> Route based on hostname (api.example.com vs www.example.com)
            -> Route based on HTTP method (GET vs POST)
            -> Terminate SSL and inspect encrypted traffic
            -> Set and read cookies for sticky sessions
            -> Add, modify, or remove HTTP headers
            -> Compress responses
            -> Cache content


        When to Use Each



    Use Layer 4 when:

        -> You need maximum performance
        -> You are load balancing non-HTTP traffic (databases, game servers, custom protocols)
        -> Simple round-robin distribution is sufficient
        -> You want to pass SSL through to backends


    Use Layer 7 when:

        -> You need content-based routing (URL paths, hostnames)
        -> You want SSL termination at the load balancer
        -> You need cookie-based sticky sessions
        -> You want to add headers (like X-Forwarded-For or X-Request-ID)
        -> You want to cache or compress responses